    "  <p style=\"text-align:center; font-size:16px; font-weight:bold; color:#6A1B9A;\">\n",
    "    Notes on Time Series Decomposition\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <p>\n",
    "    <strong>Decomposition models</strong> break a time series into three main components:\n",
    "    <strong>Trend</strong>, <strong>Seasonality</strong>, and <strong>Residual (Noise)</strong>.\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <p style=\"color:#6A1B9A; font-weight:bold;\">\n",
    "    Model Type\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <ul>\n",
    "    <li>\n",
    "      <strong>model = 'additive'</strong><br>\n",
    "      Assumes:<br>\n",
    "      <em>Observed = Trend + Seasonal + Residual</em><br>\n",
    "      Best when seasonal fluctuations are relatively constant over time.\n",
    "    </li>\n",
    "    <li>\n",
    "      <strong>model = 'multiplicative'</strong><br>\n",
    "      Assumes:<br>\n",
    "      <em>Observed = Trend × Seasonal × Residual</em><br>\n",
    "      Use this when seasonal variations grow or shrink with the level of the series\n",
    "      (common in prices and demand growth).\n",
    "    </li>\n",
    "  </ul>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <p style=\"color:#6A1B9A; font-weight:bold;\">\n",
    "    Seasonal Period Definition\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <p>\n",
    "    The <strong>period</strong> parameter represents the length of one complete seasonal cycle.\n",
    "  </p>\n",
    "\n",
    "  <ul>\n",
    "    <li>\n",
    "      <strong>Hourly Data</strong>\n",
    "      <ul>\n",
    "        <li>Daily seasonality → period = 24</li>\n",
    "        <li>Weekly seasonality → pe\n"
